    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-08-08T17:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-08-08T17:00:00-05:00" n="589"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d589">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.48/968: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-08-08T18:00:00-04:00"
                            >August 8, 1935—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>124. Embassy’s despatch No. 1383, July 10, last sentence. In view of the absence
                    of conclusive evidence that the Japanese Government is responsible for refusal
                    of Japanese mills to purchase the American cotton under reference in Shanghai,
                    and in view of the statement of the Consul at Kobe that “large quantities” of
                    such cotton have been re-exported from China, the Department is of the opinion
                    that the <pb facs="0723" n="611" xml:id="pg_611"/> matter need not be discussed
                    in any way with officials of the Foreign Office.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
